WEBVTT

00:22.300 --> 00:22.860
15.

00:24.120 --> 00:25.500
The Man of the Island

00:26.600 --> 00:35.300
From the side of the hill, which was here steep and stony, a spout of gravel was dislodged and fell rattling and bounding through the trees.

00:37.380 --> 00:44.080
My eyes turned instinctively in that direction, and I saw a figure leap with great rapidity behind the trunk of a pine.

00:45.560 --> 00:50.560
What it was, whether bear or man or monkey, I could in no wise tell.

00:51.220 --> 01:00.580
It seemed dark and shaggy, more I knew not, but the terror of this new apparition brought me to a stand.

01:02.860 --> 01:11.900
I was now, it seemed, cut off upon both sides, behind me the murderers, before me this lurking nondescript.

01:14.460 --> 01:18.980
And immediately I began to prefer the dangers that I knew to those I knew not.

01:20.560 --> 01:33.580
Silver himself appeared less terrible in contrast with this creature of the woods, and I turned on my heel, and looking sharply behind me over my shoulder began to retrace my steps in the direction of the boats.

01:35.500 --> 01:41.140
Instantly the figure reappeared, and making a wide circuit began to head me off.

01:42.860 --> 01:52.620
I was tired at any rate, but had I been as fresh as when I rose, I could see it was in vain for me to contend in speed with such an adversary.

01:54.220 --> 02:04.020
From trunk to trunk the creature flitted like a deer, running manlike on two legs, but unlike any man that I had ever seen, stooping almost double as it ran.

02:05.480 --> 02:09.240
Yet a man it was, I could no longer be in doubt about that.

02:11.900 --> 02:14.940
I began to recall what I had heard of cannibals.

02:16.200 --> 02:27.320
I was within an ace of calling for help, but the mere fact that he was a man, however wild, had somehow reassured me, and my fear of silver began to revive in proportion.

02:28.280 --> 02:33.600
I stood still, therefore, and cast about for some method of escape.

02:34.940 --> 02:40.600
And as I was so thinking, the recollection of my pistol flashed into my mind.

02:43.400 --> 02:56.940
As soon as I remembered I was not defenseless, courage glowed again in my heart, and I set my face resolutely for this man of the island, and walked briskly towards him.

02:59.380 --> 03:10.420
He was concealed by this time behind another tree trunk, but he must have been watching me closely, for as soon as I began to move in his direction, he reappeared and took a step to meet me.

03:11.140 --> 03:22.540
Then he hesitated, drew back, came forward again, and at last, to my wonder and confusion, he threw himself on his knees and held out his clasped hands in supplication.

03:24.640 --> 03:26.200
At that I once more stopped.

03:27.300 --> 03:28.620
Who are you, I asked?

03:31.080 --> 03:35.980
Ben Gunn, he answered, and his voice sounded hoarse and awkward like a rusty lock.

03:36.220 --> 03:42.900
I'm poor Ben Gunn, I am, and I haven't spoken with a Christian these three years.

03:45.440 --> 03:51.120
I could now see that he was a white man like myself, and that his features were even pleasing.

03:51.700 --> 03:55.360
His skin, wherever it was exposed, was burnt by the sun.

03:56.060 --> 04:01.420
Even his lips were black, and his fair eyes looked quite startling in so dark a face.

04:02.480 --> 04:07.040
Of all the beggar men that I had seen or fancied, he was the chief for raggedness.

04:07.780 --> 04:25.140
He was clothed with tatters of old ship's canvas and old sea cloth, and this extraordinary patchwork was all held together by a system of the most various and incongruous fastenings, brass buttons, bits of stick, and loops of tarrygaskin.

04:27.240 --> 04:33.400
About his waist he wore an old brass buckled leather belt, which was one thing solid in his whole accoutrement.

04:36.020 --> 04:38.560
Three years, I cried, were you shipwrecked?

04:40.160 --> 04:43.600
Nay, mate, said he, marooned.

04:45.220 --> 04:59.280
I had heard the word, and I knew it stood for a horrible kind of punishment common enough among the buccaneers, in which the offender is put ashore with a little powder and shot, and left behind on some desolate and distant island.

05:01.200 --> 05:07.720
Marooned three years a-gone, he continued, and lived on goats since then, and berries, and oysters.

05:09.120 --> 05:12.340
Wherever a man is, says I, a man can do for himself.

05:13.520 --> 05:16.920
But, mate, my heart is sore for Christian diet.

05:17.920 --> 05:20.740
You mightn't happen to have a piece of cheese about you now.

05:21.460 --> 05:31.780
No, well, many's the long night I've dreamed of cheese, toasted mostly, and woke up again, and here I were.

05:34.200 --> 05:39.100
If ever I can get aboard again, said I, you shall have cheese by the stone.

05:40.700 --> 05:52.000
All this time he had been feeling the stuff of my jacket, smoothing my hands, looking at my boots, and generally in the intervals of his speech, showing a childish pleasure in the presence of a fellow creature.

05:53.040 --> 05:56.560
But at my last words he perked up into a kind of startled sliness.

05:58.660 --> 06:05.700
If ever you can get aboard again, says you, he repeated, why now, who's to hinder you?

06:07.180 --> 06:09.780
Not you, I know, was my reply.

06:11.020 --> 06:12.800
And right you was, he cried.

06:14.140 --> 06:16.200
Now you, what do you call yourself, mate?

06:18.840 --> 06:20.020
Jim, I told him.

06:21.440 --> 06:25.160
Jim, Jim, says he, quite pleased apparently.

06:26.180 --> 06:31.180
Well now, Jim, I've lived that rough as you'd be ashamed to hear of.

06:31.180 --> 06:37.160
Now, for instance, you wouldn't think I had a pious mother to look at me, he asked.

06:38.580 --> 06:41.120
Why, no, not in particular, I answered.

06:41.700 --> 06:55.280
Ah, well, said he, but I had remarkable pious, and I was a civil pious boy, and could rattle off my cataclysm that fast as you couldn't tell one word from another.

06:56.620 --> 07:04.360
And here's what it come to, Jim, and it begun with Chuck Farthen on the blessed gravestones.

07:06.160 --> 07:09.400
That's what it begun with, but it went further than that.

07:11.300 --> 07:17.840
And so my mother told me, and predicted the whole thing she did, the pious woman.

07:18.660 --> 07:21.100
But it were providence that put me here.

07:21.100 --> 07:26.580
I've sought it all out in this here lonely island, and I'm back on piety.

07:27.380 --> 07:34.860
You don't catch me tasting rum so much, but just a thimbleful for luck, of course, the first chance I have.

07:35.800 --> 07:40.760
I'm bound I'll be good, and I see the way too.

07:41.040 --> 07:48.080
And Jim, looking all round him and lowering his voice to a whisper, I'm rich.

07:49.320 --> 07:58.250
I now felt sure that the poor fellow had gone crazy in his solitude, and I suppose I must have shown the feeling on my face, for he repeated the statement hotly.

07:59.100 --> 08:08.300
Rich, rich, I says, and I'll tell you what, I'll make a man of you, Jim. Ah, Jim, you'll bless your stars, you will.

08:08.920 --> 08:11.020
He was the first that found me.

08:12.680 --> 08:22.780
And at this there came suddenly a lowering shadow over his face, and he tightened his grasp upon my hand and raised a forefinger threateningly before my eyes.

08:23.780 --> 08:29.900
Now, Jim, you tell me true. That ain't Flint's ship, he asked.

08:32.560 --> 08:34.900
At this I had a happy inspiration.

08:36.040 --> 08:40.560
I began to believe that I had found an ally, and I answered him at once.

08:41.020 --> 08:46.460
It's not Flint's ship, and Flint is dead, but I'll tell you true as you ask me.

08:46.720 --> 08:51.340
There are some of Flint's hands aboard. Worse luck for the rest of us.

08:52.640 --> 08:59.000
Not a man with one leg, he gasped.

08:59.380 --> 09:06.220
Silver, I asked. Ah, silver, says he. That were his name.

09:08.520 --> 09:11.520
He's the cook and the ringleader, too.

09:12.960 --> 09:17.300
He was still holding me by the wrist, and at that he gave it quite a ring.

09:20.480 --> 09:28.440
If you was sent by Long John, says he, I'm as good as pork, and I know it.

09:29.140 --> 09:31.120
But where was you, do you suppose?

09:32.880 --> 09:41.420
I had made my mind up in a moment, and by way of answer told him the whole story of our voyage and the predicament in which we found ourselves.

09:42.180 --> 09:46.860
He heard me with the keenest interest, and when I had done, he patted me on the head.

09:48.240 --> 09:54.400
You're a good lad, Jim, said he, and you're all in a clove hitch, ain't you?

09:55.000 --> 10:00.520
Well, you just put your trust in Ben Gunn. Ben Gunn's the man to do it.

10:00.520 --> 10:09.540
Would you think it likely now that your squire would prove a liberal-minded one in case of help, him being in a clove hitch, as you remark?

10:11.360 --> 10:14.340
I told him the squire was the most liberal of men.

10:14.980 --> 10:24.480
Aye, but you see, returned Ben Gunn, I didn't mean giving me a gate to keep and a suit of livery clothes and such.

10:24.480 --> 10:37.720
That's not my mark, Jim. What I mean is, would he be likely to come down to the tune of, say, one thousand pounds out of money that's as good as a man's own already?

10:39.860 --> 10:42.280
I'm sure he would, said I.

10:44.120 --> 10:46.160
As it was, all hands were to share.

10:46.760 --> 10:51.020
And passage home, he added with a look of great shrewdness.

10:51.780 --> 11:00.260
Why, I cried, the squire's a gentleman, and besides, if we got rid of the others, we should want you to help work the vessel home.

11:02.160 --> 11:07.500
Ah, said he, so you would, and he seemed very much relieved.

11:08.980 --> 11:14.380
Now I'll tell you what, he went on. So much I'll tell you no more.

11:15.220 --> 11:21.520
I were in Flint's ship when he buried the treasure, he and six along, six strong seamen.

11:22.640 --> 11:27.700
They was ashore nigh a week, and us standing off in the old walrus.

11:28.640 --> 11:37.280
One fine day up went the signal, and here come Flint by himself in a little boat, and his head done up in a blue scarf.

11:37.500 --> 11:43.080
The sun was getting up, and mortal white he looked about the cut water.

11:44.360 --> 11:49.520
But there he was, you mind, and not the six all dead, dead and buried.

11:49.880 --> 11:55.040
How he done it, not a ban, a board, us could make out.

11:55.600 --> 12:01.260
It was a battle, murder, and sudden death, least ways, him against six.

12:02.000 --> 12:06.680
Billy Bones was the mate, Long John, he was the quartermaster.

12:07.500 --> 12:15.960
And they asked him where the treasure was. Ah, says he, you can go ashore if you like and stay, he says.

12:16.360 --> 12:19.000
But as for the ship, she'll beat up for more.

12:21.940 --> 12:25.520
By thunder, that's what he said.

12:28.120 --> 12:33.700
Well, I was in another ship three years back, and we sighted this island.

12:33.700 --> 12:38.140
Boys, said I, here's Flint's treasure, let's land and find it.

12:38.620 --> 12:44.840
But the captain was displeased at that, but my mess-mates were all of a mind and landed.

12:45.380 --> 12:50.060
Twelve days they looked for it, and every day they had worse word of me.

12:50.860 --> 12:53.600
Until one fine morning all hands went aboard.

12:54.920 --> 13:01.900
As for you, Benjamin Gunn, says they, here's a musket, they says, and a spade and a pickaxe.

13:01.900 --> 13:06.820
You can stay here and find Flint's money for yourself, they says.

13:08.360 --> 13:16.460
Well, Jim, three years have I been here, and not a bite a Christian diet from that day to this.

13:17.100 --> 13:23.220
But now you look here, look at me. Do I look like a man before the mast?

13:23.640 --> 13:26.940
No, says you, no I weren't neither, I says.

13:28.980 --> 13:31.260
And with that he winked and pinched me hard.

13:31.900 --> 13:36.300
Just you mention them words to your squire, Jim, he went on.

13:37.060 --> 13:39.400
Nor he weren't neither, that's the words.

13:39.900 --> 13:44.600
Three years he were the man of this island, light and dark, fair and rain.

13:45.180 --> 13:52.460
And sometimes he would maybe think upon a prayer, says you, and sometimes he would maybe think of his old mother.

13:53.480 --> 13:55.880
So be as she's alive, you'll say.

13:56.740 --> 14:04.080
But the most part of Gunn's time, this is what you'll say, the most part of his time was took up with another matter.

14:05.160 --> 14:07.620
And then you'll give him a nip like I do.

14:09.180 --> 14:12.220
And he pinched me again in the most confidential manner.

14:13.200 --> 14:18.980
Then, he continued, then you'll laugh when you'll say this, Gunn is a good man, you'll say.

14:18.980 --> 14:30.160
And he puts a precious sight more confidence, precious sight, mind that, in a gentleman born than in these gentlemen, a fortune having been one himself.

14:32.100 --> 14:38.060
Well, I said, I don't understand one word that you've been saying, but that's neither here nor there.

14:38.640 --> 14:40.020
For how am I to get on board?

14:40.800 --> 14:45.060
Ah, said he, that's the hitch for sure.

14:45.060 --> 14:49.500
Well, there's my boat that I made with my two hands.

14:50.140 --> 14:51.820
I keep her under the white rock.

14:51.940 --> 14:55.800
If the worst come to the worst, we might try that after dark.

14:56.660 --> 14:58.920
Hi, he broke out.

14:59.020 --> 14:59.700
What's that?

15:01.320 --> 15:09.100
For just then, although the sun had still an hour or two to run, all the echoes of the island awoke and bellowed to the thunder of a cannon.

15:10.560 --> 15:13.040
They've begun to fight, I cried, follow me.

15:13.040 --> 15:16.360
And I began to run towards the anchorage.

15:17.240 --> 15:24.140
My terrors all forgotten, while close at my side, the marooned man and his goat skins trotted easily and lightly.

15:25.540 --> 15:27.280
Left, left, says he.

15:28.920 --> 15:30.640
Keep to your left hand, mate, Jim.

15:31.860 --> 15:33.140
Under the trees with you.

15:34.020 --> 15:35.760
There's where I killed my first goat.

15:36.160 --> 15:42.000
They don't come down here now, they're all mastheaded on them mountings for fear of Benjamin Gunn.

15:42.000 --> 15:45.500
Ah, and there's the setamary.

15:46.020 --> 15:47.540
Cemetery, he must have meant.

15:48.040 --> 15:49.220
You see them mounds.

15:49.860 --> 15:53.100
I come here and pray now and then.

15:53.520 --> 15:57.340
When I thought maybe a Sunday would be about due.

15:58.180 --> 16:01.500
It weren't quite a chapel, but it seemed more solemn-like.

16:02.320 --> 16:05.160
And then, says you, Ben Gunn was short-handed.

16:05.520 --> 16:09.580
No chapling, no so much as a Bible and a flag, you says.

16:10.660 --> 16:14.620
So he kept talking as I ran, neither expecting nor receiving an answer.

16:15.560 --> 16:21.020
The cannon shot was followed, after a considerable interval by a volley of small arms.

16:21.640 --> 16:22.580
Another pause.

16:23.460 --> 16:31.340
And then, not a quarter of a mile in front of me, I beheld the Union Jack flutter in the air above a wood.

16:33.440 --> 16:35.020
End of chapter fifteen.

